Experiment 4: Activity Selection Problem

The Problem: You are given n activities with their start and finish times. Select the maximum number of activities that can be performed by a single person, assuming that a person can only work on a single activity at a time.
1. Theory: The Greedy Choice

This problem is solved using a Greedy Algorithm. A greedy algorithm builds up a solution piece by piece, always choosing the next piece that offers the most immediate benefit.

For activity selection, what is the best "greedy" choice?

    Should we pick the shortest activity first? No, it might start in the middle of the day and block two other activities.

    Should we pick the one that starts earliest? No, it might take 10 hours and block everything else.

    The correct choice: Always pick the next available activity that finishes the earliest.

Why? Because finishing an activity as early as possible leaves the maximum amount of remaining time to schedule more activities!
2. The Approach

    Sort: Take all your activities and sort them in ascending order based on their finish times.

    Select the First: The first activity in the sorted list will always be selected because it finishes earliest and leaves the most room.

    Iterate and Compare: Go through the rest of the sorted activities one by one.

        If the start time of the current activity is greater than or equal to the finish time of the last activity you selected, you can perform it! Add it to your list.

        If the start time overlaps with your last selected activity, skip it.

Complexity Analysis

Let n be the number of activities.

    Time Complexity: * Sorting the activities based on their finish times takes O(nlogn) time.

        Iterating through the sorted list to pick non-overlapping activities takes O(n) time.

        Total Time Complexity: O(nlogn). (Note: If the input arrays are already sorted by finish time, the complexity is just O(n)).

    Space Complexity: O(n) because we are creating a new combined list of tuples and a list to store the selected activities. If we just wanted to count the max number of activities without storing them, we could do it in O(1) auxiliary space.
